      <description>&lt;div id="storytext" class="storytext storylocation linkLocation"&gt;       &lt;div id="resg-s1-85690" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 4686;         --source-height: 3138;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4686x3138+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F79%2F82%2F228e14bd4210993e5cd9dd116ce6%2Fap11082413159.jpg" class="img" alt="Eileen and Doug Flockhart look at a chalkboard announcing the birth of their seventh grandchild on the porch of their home in Exeter, N.H., Wednesday, Aug. 24, 2011." fetchpriority="high" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Eileen and Doug Flockhart look at a chalkboard announcing the birth of their seventh grandchild on the porch of their home in Exeter, N.H., Wednesday, Aug. 24, 2011.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Elise Amendola/AP                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Mothers and fathers have had their days. On Sep. 7, it's the grandma and grandpa's turn. In 1978, President Jimmy Carter &lt;a href="https://grandparentsday.org/grandparentsweek/about/" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;u&gt;signed a proclamation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt; dedicating the first Sunday after Labor Day to celebrate grandparents. It's a day to recognize the wisdom, perspective and fundamental civic values that grandparents provide.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;This year, NPR wants to hear from grandparents who are new to their role. Have you just become a grandparent, or are you expecting your first grandchild soon? Share your experience with us, and you could be featured in an upcoming issue of the &lt;em&gt;Up First &lt;/em&gt;newsletter.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Please submit responses by Sep. 3.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;See some of your responses — and get the news you need to start your day — by &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/newsletter/news" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;u&gt;subscribing to our newsletter&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;div id="resg-s1-85689-100" class="bucketwrap statichtml"&gt;             &lt;iframe src="https://npr.formstack.com/forms/are_you_a_new_grandparent_npr_wants_to_hear_from_you_for_national_grandparent_s_day" title="Formstack Form" width="100%" height="1200"&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;     &lt;!-- END ID="RESG-S1-85689-100" CLASS="BUCKETWRAP STATICHTML" --&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
